====================== Switches ======================

- Switching is the process of data WITHIN a network
  - Switches are devices whose primary purpose is switching
- Therefore, all devices commmunicating through a switch belong to the same network

- Switches use and maintain a MAC Address Table (Switch Port --> MAC Address)
  - Each connection to a switch from a device will have a "Switch Port" number. These numbers are generated by the switch.

Exemplary MAC Address Table
    ___________________
   [  7  -->    a1a1   ]
   |  8  -->    b2b2   |
   |  9  -->    c3c3   |
   [  10 -->    d4d4   ]
    ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯


Switches can only perform THREE actions: Learn, Flood, Forward

1. Learn:
   - When a frame arrives at the Switch, the switch records the source MAC address and the corresponding port number in its 
MAC address table.

2. Flood:
   - If the switch doesn't know the destination port for a received frame (e.g., the destination MAC address is not in its 
table), it "floods" the frame to all ports except the one it arrived on.
   - This ensures that the frame reaches its destination even if the switch hasn't learned its location yet.

3. Forward:
   - Once the switch has learned the MAC addresses of connected devices, it can forward frames directly to the specific port 
connected to the destination device.
   - This unicast transmission is more efficient than flooding, as it sends the frame only to the intended recipient.


