Switches are ONLY concerned with the Layer 2 Header. They do not care about Layer 3 Headers. 


========== OVERVIEW ==========

- Data THROUGH a Switch
Switches have a MAC Address, as well as an IP Address.
However, when we are sending data through a switch, the IP/MAC Address of the Switch is ignored.

The switch has a MAC Address table, where it has mappings of the Switch Port and connected host MAC Address saved.
LEARN: If the switch doesn't have a record of the frame's source MAC Address in it's MAC Table, it will LEARN the mapping and save it to its table.
FLOOD: If the switch doesn't know the mapping for the destination MAC Address, it will flood every port with the data.
FORWARD: If the switch finds the destination MAC Address in its MAC Address Table, it'll be able to simply FORWARD the data directly to the destination
This is done in unicast transmission, as flooding is inefficient. it sends the frame only to the intended recipient.


- Data TO a Switch
If we wanted to send data TO a switch, the switch would essentially act as a host.
The switch would have to follow all the communication rules of a host.

